https://github.com/go-git/go-git/commit/5cab3a7bbd5ce5573c4b188abe459a371b84cae7","id":3303433750,"in_reply_to":null,"line":null,"path":"docs/convert-sha256.md","user":"pjbgf"}
{"body":"Perhaps we could switch `--sign` with `--sign-mode` which defaults to `none`, but then has `tips` (current implementation) and later could have an `all`, which could sign all objects, to support workflows whereby users want to enforce all commits/tags being signed.","id":3303536888,"in_reply_to":null,"line":null,"path":"docs/convert-sha256.md","user":"pjbgf"}
{"body":"Not sure I understand the premise here. Are there any concerns on signing tags in place?","id":3303550212,"in_reply_to":null,"line":737,"path":"cmd/git-sync/internal/sha256convert/sha256convert.go","user":"pjbgf"}
{"body":"Already addressed in the current revision — `discoverReachable` is now an iterative DFS that checks `ctx.Err()` once per object at the top of the stack loop, so Ctrl-C interrupts discovery promptly. This comment was anchored to an earlier commit (`f6e944c`), before that rewrite landed.","id":3323430856,"in_reply_to":3302581515,"line":1135,"path":"cmd/git-sync/internal/sha256convert/sha256convert.go","user":"nodo"}
{"body":"Confirmed, thanks — the pinned `v6.0.0-alpha.4` derives the hash format from the store config. Dropped the hand-rolled loose-object writer entirely; translation now goes through `dst.NewEncodedObject` + `SetEncodedObject`, so the returned hash and the on-disk path are both SHA256. Updated this implementation note too. (e7e4a1a)","id":3323431355,"in_reply_to":3303433750,"line":null,"path":"docs/convert-sha256.md","user":"nodo"}
{"body":"Done — `--sign` is now `--sign-mode {none,tips}`, defaulting to `none`. Kept the enum small and forward-compatible so an `all` mode (sign every commit/tag) can be added later without changing the flag's shape. (e7e4a1a)","id":3323432075,"in_reply_to":3303536888,"line":null,"path":"docs/convert-sha256.md","user":"nodo"}
{"body":"`--sign-mode tips` signs *branch tips*, not the repo's tags. A branch (`refs/heads/x`) isn't itself a signable object — only commits and tags are — so attesting a branch's whole history means wrapping its tip in a signed annotated tag, which is what `refs/tags/converted/<branch>` is; its signature transitively covers every ancestor via the parent chain.

Re-signing the repo's *own* tags in place is a separate thing — that's the `all` mode the new `--sign-mode` enum leaves room for. No correctness concern with signing tags in place per se; it's just out of scope for `tips`, which needs only one signed object per branch to attest the entire reachable set (in-place tag signing alone would leave the commit history unattested).","id":3323432761,"in_reply_to":3303550212,"line":737,"path":"cmd/git-sync/internal/sha256convert/sha256convert.go","user":"nodo"}
{"body":"^ @pjbgf - does this make sense?","id":3323441890,"in_reply_to":3303550212,"line":737,"path":"cmd/git-sync/internal/sha256convert/sha256convert.go","user":"nodo"}

